,Not Recommended,319140,30248219,Posted: 28 February,all,Einer Von Denen,"This could be a fun game but it feels so cheap. The only checkpoints are before bosses and these are the only points where you can replenish your health during a level. That wouldn't be so bad if the big monsters weren't placed in the most unfair ways possible.You jump out of the water? Too bad. A big snail shoots you in the face for 2 of your 4 health points. If you die you have to play everything all over again and the levels are not fun. They are so slow, because everything hits so hard while being able to tank so many of your shots, you can't really see what's coming next and enemies will attack you from blind spots of the screen. You can't make mistakes or 8 minutes of slow grinding are for nothing. Aforementioned snail takes something like 15 hits and just shoots bullets in a straight path. The difficulty is in repetition. Jump over the bullet, shoot the snail in the face, rinse repeat 10 times and the snail is dead. If you mess up one jump, you lose half your health. This is just cheap.Then there are the bosses. They all look the same but have some extra attacks. They can randomly heal themselves. With no counterplay on your part. Fun. Otherwise they hit like trucks and are situated in tiny rooms like old Mega Man bosses. If you managed to defeat a boss, well done. Have fun backtracking through the level while dying over and over again. You can only save at your ship. Fun.Some could say ""git gud"" and maybe this game isn't for me. I usually enjoy difficult games but this one just feels like cheap difficulty to me. Take all the parts that made Mega Man or the original Metroid unfun and claim it's cool and retro. There is a reason why certain things are handled differently in modern games. All this is made more infuriating by the fixed jump height. Even in Mega Man you could vary your jumping height. It just feels like a struggle to control the character.There is an illusion of a Metroid