,Recommended,319140,22788142,"Posted: 3 May, 2016",all,mikew,"Xeodrifter is a neat little Metroid-like. The abilities are unique and used to good effect with some inventive environment-traversal tricks. I liked the setup of moving between four different planets instead of having four different areas interconnected on the same planet. The weapon-upgrading system is excellent; being able to experiment with different weapon types by redistributing your upgrade points at any time is a great touch.The game has its weak points, but they're more on the order of minor gripes than major flaws. At first I didn't like the way my character jumped (always reaching maximum height instead of varying depending on how hard I pressed), but I got used to it. You fight the same boss character repeatedly, which may be a little tedious, but the fight changes over time, and its recurrence plays a role in the (admittedly thin) story. I really wish I could have cycled through weapons without going to the pause screen; the left and right triggers on my controller were just begging to be used. I also wish I could have used the thumbstick for movement, because the absolute worst part of this game was my 360 controller's d-pad.Xeodrifter doesn't overstay its welcome; my six-hour playtime is quite a bit longer than necessary because I spent some time jumping against every wall I could, trying to find a couple of secret passages that were eluding me. But despite it being a little on the short side, it felt like the right length to me, and made for a nice bite-sized weekend diversion. I have a big soft spot for Metroidvanias in general, so I'm predisposed to giving a thumbs-up here, but I found a lot to like."
,Recommended,319140,13352756,"Posted: 13 December, 2014",all,Arkveveen,"Xeodrifter is a neat little gem with heavy inspiration from Metroid and Super Metroid. It's a simple little game that won't take you much longer than 5 hours, but it's full of enough secrets, tough bosses, and fun abilities to excuse the short length of the game. However, it doesn't feel complete as a result.Xeodrifter, in a nutshell, is a tasty little retro romp that will satisfy your appetite if you miss Metroid or Super Metroid!Still waiting on you, Nintendo, or whoever is forcing Metroid to float in limbo..."
,Not Recommended,319140,29723993,Posted: 5 February,all,Stalinbrad,"How this got a 9/10 from Destructoid, I'll never know. While this is a beautiful, beautiful game, and it has some very interesting design, the gameplay has a lot of glaring flaws. I really hope the devs actually ready these reviews and take notice, because I think that the main problems with this game happen to be a direct result of design choices, rather than simple sloppy work -- barring the bosses. I don't like fighting the same enemy over and over and over again.Starting Xeodrifter is probably the most brutal part of the game. The starting health is absurd for someone who is just learning how the game works, and the trial-by-fire method seems to be counter-intuitive here. The fact that the developers chose to assuage the pain of this by adding in a checkpoint system instead of culling back the gauntlet, or giving the player better footing to start with is something that bothers me immensely. It says to me, ""We want our game to be hard, but we don't really want to think about what that means."" There are several points throughout my first hour of playing the game where exhausting enemies with the same simple pattern are simply copy and pasted. They have an absurd amount of health for what I can only glean is to test if the player can jump over the same pellet they shoot repeatedly. Now, to be fair, a few times to deal with the same attack at once is fine. Fifteen times, and you're just being mean.I have fought five bosses, and every single one of them is the same archetype. Each of them seems to have a moveset that builds upon the last, which would be interesting if there were some other boss-type to compare them against. Since there hasn't been, I can't say that there's anything special about these additional attack patterns. What I can say, however, is that the developers seem to dislike the idea of you using phase-shifting in a fight when you're not supposed to. While there are certain moves and patterns where phase-shifting to the background is something you're clearly supposed to do, when you're not supposed to, the boss monster will go positively ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥. That is to say, the game punishes you for using a tool that it has given you. That's not fun at all. It sends a clear message: There is only one way to approach this situation, and if you don't approach it that way, you are playing the game wrong. Not allowing the player to have flexibility with the tools you've given them makes using those tools boring and predictable. Bossfights are just an exasperating exercise in recognizing and repeatedly dodging patterns while shooting back with absolutely no room for personal preference or playstyle.The weapon system would appear, at first, to be this game's saving grace. After all, you're given a measure of custimization with your guns. But from what I've tried, it largely makes no difference aside from clearing out enemies that are purposefully and awkwardly placed.The tight mechanics might work in another setting a lot more, but I think with the way the game is set up, especially as an alien exploration metroidvania-esque game, simple and forced playstyle and plain pattern memorization just make for bland and tasteless experience. I really want to like this game more, because again, it is quite beautiful, but it's boring, meticulous, and completely unrewarding.If you're not dissuaded by what I nitpicked at with this game, go ahead and pick it up, but for my time with this game, I couldn't and wouldn't recommend this to anyone who didn't already have their heart set on it. It's just a disappointing experience all around."
