76561198077323062,Not Recommended,319140,23129794,"Posted: 21 May, 2016",all,Photon,"Got this on sale and I've beaten five of seven bosses. Though perhaps unintentional, Xeodrifter seems to ride too hard on the ""upgrade hunt"" aspect of the game, because the package as a whole feels terribly monotonous. It starts slow, briefly shows a flash or two of brilliance, but quickly settles into running you in circles.First and perhaps most notably, combat is incredibly boring outside of boss fights. Enemies have static patterns they rarely deviate from. One moves back and forward in a straight line, another stays in place firing bullets in four directions, etc. The problem here is that most enemies rarely play ""aggressor;"" they don't change their bullet trajectories, they don't chase... they just carry on with their patterns indefinitely until you take them out. In fact, you could probably avoid and ignore half (if not more) of the enemies in the game and be just fine.As a result, level traversal is a chore: move a little, defeat a bullet sponge, continue. It gets old fast. Further exasperating the issue are quirks like no variable jump height and the inability to aim up while walking. This can make taking down enemiess even more tedious. On top of all that, defeated foes don't give health drops (or at least not any that I've seen,) meaning you won't see many of them. Checkpoints are also infrequent. Admittedly, I can see where some people would consider this gauntlet-style trek a challenge worth accepting; however, with combat fairly unengaging and more of a literal roadblock than an actual fight, who wants to repeat it two or three times?The end result is that the exploration the game is supposedly banking on ultimately falls flat. Especially early, it can be a constant stop-and-go firefight where impatiently trying to increase your pace can easily lead to accidental damage.Now, I did say that there were flashes of good. The weapon customization system is neat, and a welcome one at that. I was quite happy to beef up my gun for quicker takedowns and I particularly liked the ""sine-wave"" upgrade. Also, despite sharing some already mentioned repetition issues, the boss fights are decent enough. They are probably where some of the powerups see their best utilization, especially the plane shifting upgrade. True, bosses can be spongy and predictable like the grunts, but not even close to the same extent.But its unfortunate to me that these pluses more or less made the game more bearable, not took it from good to great. As the game progresses and more upgrades become available, things still failed to pick up significantly. If that wasn't bad enough, the game is fairly bad at pushing you towards where you should go next. This wouldn't be so bad if not for the above AND later on it often seems to put ""gates"" too close to each other. There is literally one spot in the game where its practically four or five gates one right after the other, each representing the next powerup you should obtain. Why? What's the point? It gives this false sense of discovery when you can finally open that ""locked door,"" only to find another one directly after it with almost no iterim material or reward. I feel the game misses some opportunities to reward that easy-going, poking around that usually comes with the territory.I stuck with it for awhile, but I'm just not enjoying it that much. I still kinda want to do due diligence and finish it (I hear its short,) but even so. Bottom line: it flatlined for me almost immediately and never made a full recovery. Quite a shame, as part of me really feels a great opportunity just didn't materialize properly."
