76561198052657232,Not Recommended,319140,29774425,Posted: 7 February,all,Kasdarack,"So close.Xeodrifter is ...almost there. It has all of the elements that make a Metroidish game, but lacks something in every department.Controls: Once I mapped the directional pad to my analong stick the controls responded well. However, the lack of diagonals and the fixed jump height are kinda unforgivable in 201X and hurt playability. Almost every type of special movement being mapped to B instead of making use of the left shoulder button hurt as well.Features: Pretty standard fare for health, 1 = 1 and all. The weapon upgrade system was neat in theory, but in actuality you're never going to allocate points to at least two of the gimmicks. The ""suit"" upgrades are also standard fare, which isn't bad but there was not much original about the game. Worth noting is the ability to shift from fore to background, which is probably the best executed of the upgrades.Graphics: Neat little 8-bit style graphics, if a bit bland in spots. The ability to shift focus from foreground to background was kinda cool and done well from a graphical standpoint and deserves some praise. Some bits look like they were ripped straight from Metroid which I have mixed feelings about because hey, at least they looked good. The primary weapon could have used better looking bullets.Sound: The music was pretty atrocious. Just a bar or two repeating for each of the zones. The SFX were also bland and repetitive to the point of annoyance. This is one area where the game could use some work by someone experienced in SFX and soundtrack. It is possible that the DLC addresses this; I can't say as I didn't spend the extra dollar.Now... the worst bit. There are very few enemy types and only one of the standard enemies has any sort of intelligent attack pattern. The Bosses are... all the same boss but with one extra type of ability thrown into the mix and enough extra HP each time to make sure they go through the list of all of the previous attack types. This is unfortunate as unique bosses really would have helped this game feel a little dynamic.I really want to give this game a positive review and a recommend as it is right on the verge of being a cool game. But in honesty I feel more like I wasted a few hours of my day than I do satisfied that I finished it.  For the price on sale I don't feel like I wasted money, but I wish I had those hours back."
76561197996630152,Recommended,319140,33297610,Posted: 5 July,all,V Viper,"Xeodrifter is a fairly uninspired Metroid clone, without enough unique twists or personal style to really make it stand out. Still, if you're gonna rip off something, Metroid's a pretty good base to use, and the result is still somewhat amusing (if you can get it at a reduced price).If I were to make a direct comparison to any Metroid game, Xeodrifter is probably most like Metroid Prime 3: instead of one large world consisting of tunnels and caves all networked together, the game is split up into several smaller labyrinthine worlds, and you can travel between them using your spaceship in the main hub screen. Unfortunately, unlike Prime 3, each world only has a single teleporter that will let you return to your ship, and your ship is the only place you can save your game and fully restore your health. Each world isn't overly large so you won't have to backtracktoomuch to return to your vessel, but it still would've been nice if there had been more docking ports unlocked as you progressed.Gameplay is pretty standard Metroid fare too. That classic feeling of excitement, knowing that you've discovered new powers and can use them to reach places you couldn't before, never really gets old. Still, Xeodrifter does almost nothing to make it stand out from its inspiration. The only thing it does that's kind of original is its weapon upgrade system, which allows you to allot upgrade points to your firearm in one of 5 different categories: projectile speed, damage, rate of fire, spread, and wave. You can add and remove points from each category freely, and even save up to 3 presets. I enjoyed experimenting and seeing which combination worked best in various combat situations.One combat situation that came up often was boss fights, or rather a single boss fight repeated throughout the game. Yes, there's only one boss that you fight time after time, which is something a lot of reviewers have taken issue with. It's a little odd, but I didn't really hate it, as each time the boss shows up again, it's learned a few new techniques. By the end of the game, its moveset is vast, and I enjoyed applying my accumulated knowledge of all its various tells in order to defeat it. I wouldn't have minded a few completely unique bosses, sure, but I didn't have a huge problem with the method the developers ultimately used.Before concluding this review, and without giving too much away, I'd like to briefly mention the ending of the game. Xeodrifter is generally fairly bright and cutesy, but this is in stark contrast to an event at its climax. It presents a moment with some emotional impact on the player, but then fails to explore it, quickly sweeping the moment under the rug and returning to the game's usual happy-go-lucky ways for the credits. I'll give the developers credit for crafting a scenario that stuck in my mind, but I felt it was a mistake: adding this moment seemed unnecessary and only serves to slightly sour the overall experience.In the end, I think Xeodrifter isjustworthy of recommendation, but only on sale. The crude graphics and sound, on par with a very early Game Boy Advance game, won't impress anyone. And even if you're a slowpoke like me and take your time checking and re-checking every corner of the game world for secrets, you're probably only going to wring about 3 hours out of the experience at most, with seemingly no post-game content to keep you coming back. Still, I can't deny that I had fun playing it. It may not be that soothing ointment that cures you of your Metroid itch, but Xeodrifter will give it a brief scratch if desired."
