,Recommended,319140,15306939,"Posted: 11 April, 2015",all,edgeblade,"Xeodrifter takes a lot of inspiration from the original Metroid though with later entries advances like a map, checkpoints, and save points. The gameplay is challenging but still fun at the same time. Sometimes it can be tough to figure out what to do next if you don't remember to backtrack to previously explored planets to use your newfound powerups, but that's half the fun. The bosses while visually similar keep employing new tactics to keep you on your toes and you will have to use most (if not all) of your powerups to succeed. It's a relatively short game, but well worth the $9.99 in my opinion.  It took me about 4 hours to finish and I missed two health upgrades, which I have no idea where they could be. There are several hidden areas in the game as well, so maybe they were hidden somewhere. If you figure an average movie runs you $20+ at a theater and you might get 2 hours out of it, you're getting double your value out of Xeodrifter for half the price. If you like Metroid style games, you'll like Xeodrifter."
,Recommended,319140,15561753,"Posted: 26 April, 2015",all,Revenant,"Xeodrifter is a short but sweet Metroid-like game where the player must explore 4 unique planets to find new abilities and a number of power-ups in order to find their way home. Taking a page out of Metroid Fusion the map is separated into 4 different sections with a hub (the players ship) rather than the Super Metroid approach of a single interconnected world. Each of these levels has a number of routes which can be opened with new abilities and contain power-ups to give the player an easier time.Xeodrifter controls rather well but does suffer from a slightly floaty feel in regards to the movement. Having only used an Xbox controller I found it intuitive but would probably advise against using a keyboard.One of the power-ups the player can find is a Gun Mod. Each of these is a single point which can be used to customize the way your weapon functions. By mixing and matching these point (which can be refunded and re-added at any point) you will be able to increase the damage, firing rate and spread or even make the bullets fire in a sine wave. You can also save 3 varieties of firing modes for quick use in the future.The planets are filled with a wide array of beasts which will try and impede your progress, many of which have attack patterns players which have experienced a Metroid game will recognize. All of them have different ways of hindering the player and there was rarely a time I found myself annoyed at their placement in the world.The downside to this game is of course its length, you can probably beat this game in well under 3 hours. There is also only a single boss to battle. However each time you fight it there is a new move or 2 added to its library, making it slightly more difficult. Another variety of boss or two would have helped keep it fresh though.A final complaint is the construction of the fourth world. While all of the others have a few branching or looping paths this one is almost entirely linear. This planet just doesn't seem to have had the same attention put into its creation which is a bit of a shame.Overall anyone who is a fan of Metroid-like platform games should definitely check this one out and not be put off by the short playtime provided. Xeodrifter, while short, does not overstay its welcome and the abilities you collect from the bosses make revisiting old locations for new gear a joy."
,Recommended,319140,16836477,"Posted: 1 July, 2015",all,Frostilyte,"A short and well crafted Metroid-like game. Xeodrifter is basically a mini-metroid game meaning it heavily focuses on exploration and backtracking to find hidden goodies. I really enjoyed the well crafted levels as they helped create a feeling of organic exploration throughout the game. I also found the equipment system (or however you'd like to address it) very interesting and appreciated that I was able to customize certain aspects of how my character shot bullets at enemies.As a warning, Xeodrifter only takes 2-3 hours to complete, so if you will feel shafted buying it for 10$ (or your regional equivalent) I would recommend getting it on sale. Otherwise, if you tend to enjoy metroid-like or metroid-vania games this may be a game that you'd enjoy."
,Recommended,319140,15279780,"Posted: 9 April, 2015",all,bertaschramm,"Good: Great ""metroidish"" game, but with a new twist. Espescially the feature to switch between foreground and background is awesome. Great level design. Great pixel art. Cool music. Very fun and rewarding.Not so good: Fullscreen mode does not work when having high DPI mode enabled in Windows. You only see the upper left part of the actual game. There is only one boss enemy that you have to beat 7 times. It does have some new tricks every time, but it is still the same sprite every time, just a different color. A little more variety would have been nice. Some overpowered enemies (the pink fly).Bad: No save points, only check points before and after each boss fight. Because of that, you will have to repeat some sections very often because you cannot save and the enemies do not drop any health pickups. There are some hidden health stashes, but those a pretty rare and most of the time not in the place where you would need them. This is what bothered me most. I don't like repetitions, even if it was state of the art back in the 8-Bit days. This is one thing I do not miss from those times. ;-)Conclusion: Looking forward to a sequel!"
,Recommended,319140,16068142,"Posted: 29 May, 2015",all,pokusan,"Xeodrifter is a lot of fun, but is a little short. Let's make a quick list for you.Good:- Gun upgrades - They are kind of ambiguous, but it actually forces you to try out the different combos of how you can create your gun and allows you to choose really different build paths. Pretty cool feature!- Fun skills - You pick up skills as you progress through the game that not only help you through levels, but help you do them quicker and more efficiently. You can also manipulate them creatively to take on bosses!- Secret rooms - If you're anything like me, you'll love finding the secret rooms in here. The first secret room I stumbled upon was completely by accidentjump-running into a wall. See what you can find!- Level builds (also see ""not so good"") - The level builds are creative and once you start earning your upgrades, you're going to really appreciate the way they are constructed. There aren't many levels, but you'll be able to revisit them with your upgrades to explore even more!- Achievements - GET THEM!Not So Good:- Short game - I don't have much time down on this game and once it was done, I found myself hoping there was more, like maybe some extra content once it's beaten.- Level builds - Some of the levels builds are pretty in-depth, which is pretty awesome while you're exploring, but when going back to look for secret rooms or upgrades, some of the levels can be really long and it takes a long time to get back to the spot where you would find the secret/upgrade. I found myself sort of annoyed that I had to go through that level and run all the way back just for 1 item. Having said that, it's not a terrible feature, just ""not so good.""- Boss algorithms don't change much - [Minor Spoiler]The bosses are pretty much the same boss, but a different color, which doesn't create a ton of variety. They do, however, (after this first boss) add on to the previous boss' repertoir, so while the algorithms do change a bit, there is a bit of familiararity of skills. I could be a cool feature, but by the end of the game, it wasn't hard to take down the last boss becase you pretty much know what he is going to use the whole time.Though I wouldn't say that it necessarily takes away from the boss fights being fun.Overall, 8/10. Wish there was more, but I was engaged and excited every time I was playing this game. The devs definitely get props for this one. They made this game so refreshing and fun."
