76561198019216815,Recommended,319140,30497488,Posted: 13 March,all,Crebmen,"Xeodrifter is a Metroid-inspired 2D-platformer originally developed for the Nintendo 3DS. I went into this game without any knowledge about it, and I was pleasantly surprised by how much fun it was.There are plenty of neat gameplay ideas used to a great effect (which I won't spoil), but some of the late-game abilities are a bit under-utilized. However, knowing the limited size and scope of the game, it's excusable.The level, or WORLD DESIGN I guess you should say, is pretty darn good for the most part. It uses the game's mechanics in very clear ways that rarely leave you wondering where you're supposed to go and how you're supposed to go about it. If you want to 100% this game you'll have to back-track through the same areas over and over, but unlike metroid which had big sprawling maps with tons of different paths connecting to each other, Zeodrifter is a lot more linear and limited. I got a bit tired of going down the same areas after acquiring a new ability that allowed me to reach a spot or path I wasn't able to before. I understand they wanted to extend the longevity of the game but it wasn't the most enjoyable way of going about it from a player's perspective.Another thing the levels have are water-sections. Thankfully they're not too annoying, but they make back-tracking a chore, and I didn't enjoy them over-all.What I do enjoy is the on-the-fly weapon upgrading system which allows the player to change their weapon's capabilities on the fly, using upgrade points you pick up from secret areas (much like Metroid). It's really quick and really intuitive, and allows you to change your weapon depending on the scenario so that you can tackle it more efficiently.One slightly dissapointing thing is the boss-fights. Now there are multiple bosses in the game but they are all the same boss copy-pasted, palette-swapped, and with more attacks added to its move-set each time you encounter it. While the boss eventually gets pretty creative if you use the game's mechanics to your advantage, it does feel a bit cheap and underwhelming, especially since the FINAL BOSS feels no different than the ones before it.Over-all though I think the game is great, and is totally worth the 2-3 hours of your time.PROS:-Vibrant and clean pixel-art visuals.-Solid game feel.-World-design that cleverly uses the game's mechanics.-Challenging enemies.-Intuitive and fun weapon-upgrade system.-A bunch of secrets for 100 percenters.MIDDLE-GROUND:(most of this stuff can be excused because it is a small game made by a small studio)-Back-tracking was a bit tedious in some parts.-Copy-pasted bosses.-Movement-inertia is a bit slippery.CONS:-Water sections are a bore.-Ending is VERY underwhelming.SCORE: 8/10"
