,Recommended,319140,29731918,Posted: 5 February,all,yung crystal pepsi,"Pros:-Classic, Metroid-like feel. This game brought me back to my childhood, when I played Super, Fusion and Zero Mission to absolute death. The formula is so well-executed here that you could replace the main character with Samus and it would feel like something Nintendo made.-Unique and customizable upgrade system that encourages experimentation and strategy.-Tight, responsive controls and pixel-perfect platforming.-Great art design that is also very much inspired by Metroid-Brevity! It doesn't overstay its welcome.Cons:-...Brevity. Short games are fine, but for $10, 2-5 hours isn't a lot.-Lack of direction at first. Instead of being set in one big world, Xeodrifter consists of four planets that may appear to be accessed in any order, but you need to play them a certain order to get the appropriate power-ups to proceed. Start with the green planet first.-Lack of enemy and boss variety. There aren't many standard enemies, and there is only one actual boss in the game, who you fight multiple times, with a new type of attack added onto his pattern each time.-Lack of checkpoints and save points. You can only save on your ship, and checkpoints are only granted before and after each boss fight. When you consider that most bosses take place on the other side of the map, you find yourself having to make careful mad dashes from your ship to the boss and then back, and dying can set you back a ways, especially if you're hunting for upgrades.-High difficulty. While the game doesn't have the upside-down difficulty curve of other Metroidvania titles thanks to its health system, it's still easy to die and the game length feels padded because of that.Overall, Xeodrifter is a fun little Metroidvania game that nails the formula to a T. Maybe not the best out there, but for what it is, it's great."
